               <p>Q. Do you know the prisoner. - A. I do perfectly well.</p>
               <p>Q. Were you present at any marriage of the prisoner. - A. I was at Christs Church, Blackfriers Road, she was married to 
               <persName id="t18110403-48-person447">
                  George 
                  Clerke
               <interp inst="t18110403-48-person447" type="surname" value="Clerke"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18110403-48-person447" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18110403-48-person447" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the ceremony performed. I knew both parties. I signed the enterey that was made by the parish clerk, the date of the register is February 12th 1798. When Mr. Clerke was married he was a very young <rs id="t18110403-48-viclabel276" type="occupation">gentleman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18110403-48-victim439 t18110403-48-viclabel276"></join>, the prisoner lived <rs id="t18110403-48-deflabel277" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18110403-48-defend437 t18110403-48-deflabel277"></join> with his father, and the marriage was very much against the consent of the father, and very soon after the marriage they separated.</p>
               <p>Q. When had you seen 
